<section xml:id="sec_div_alg">
  <title>The Division Algorithm</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this section, we continue our discussion of integer division.
      We introduce vocabulary to describe the result of dividing one integer by another when the answer is not an integer.
      Next, we revisit polynomials and use polynomials to prove facts about even,
      odd, and divisors using cases.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_division_algorithm">
    <title>\subdivalg</title>
    <p>
      As we saw in <xref ref="sec_even_odd_divides"></xref>,
      sometimes when we divide one integer by another integer we get an integer answer, such as
      <me>
        40 \div 5 = \frac{40}{5} = 8
      </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      We said that 5 divides 40 and wrote <m>5 \mid 40</m>.
      Other times, we get a fraction that is not an integer, such as
      <me>
        23 \div 4= \frac{23}{4} = 5.75
      </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      We said that 4 does not divide 23 and wrote <m>4 \nmid 23</m>.
      How can we think of <m>23 \div 4</m> in terms of integers?
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_cookies_children">
      <title>Cookies and Children</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the idea of giving 23 cookies to four children to describe
          <m>23 \div 4</m> in terms of (only) integers.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Imagine that I have 23 cookies and four children.
          I want to give each child as many cookies as I can, but,
          to be fair,
          each child should have the same number of cookies as the other children.
          What should I do?
          I can give each child five cookies.
          That accounts for <m>5 \times 4 = 20</m> of the cookies,
          but I cannot evenly distribute the remaining <m>23-20=3</m> cookies without breaking them,
          which I do not want to do.
          I guess those 3 cookies are for me to eat.
          We might say <m>23 \div 4</m> is 5 cookies/child with 3 cookies remaining for me.
          We can write the equation
          <me>
            23 = 5 \times 4 + 3
          </me>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      We formalize the idea from <xref ref="exam_cookies_children"></xref> with the following theorem.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_div_alg">
      <title>The Division Algorithm</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given integers <m>a</m> and <m>n</m> with <m>n \ge 1</m>,
          when we divide <m>a</m> by <m>n</m> we get
          <me>
            a = qn + r
          </me>
          for some integers <m>q</m> and <m>r</m> such that <m>0 \le r \lt  n</m>.
          Moreover, <m>q</m> and <m>r</m> are unique.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>a</m> and <m>n</m> be integers with <m>n \ge 1</m>.
          We prove existence in the case where <m>a \ge 0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since <m>a</m> is nonnegative and <m>n \ge 1</m>,
          we can imagine giving <m>a</m> cookies to <m>n</m> children.
          First, I check to see if I have enough cookies for each child to get at least one,
          and if so,
          then I hand one cookie to each child.
          Next, I repeat that step with the remaining cookies as many times as possible.
          In the end, let's say that each child gets <m>q</m> cookies.
          In total, I gave <m>q \times n=qn</m> cookies to the children,
          so there are
          <me>
            a-qn=r
          </me>
          cookies leftover for me.
          Adding <m>qn</m> to each side of the equation we get
          <me>
            a = qn+r
          </me>.
          Because I checked there were enough cookies for each child to get one, I never run out of cookies,
          and so <m>r \ge 0</m>.
          On the other hand,
          any time I still have enough cookies to give each child another cookie, I would do that.
          Therefore, the final number of remaining cookies must be strictly less than the number of children and so <m>r \lt n</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      The integers <m>q</m> and <m>r</m> in the Division Algorithm <xref ref="thm_div_alg"/> have special names.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_quo_rem_div_mod">
      <title>Quotient, Remainder, \fn{div}, and \fn{mod}</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>a</m> and <m>n</m> be integers with <m>n \ge 1</m> and let <m>q</m> and <m>r</m> be integers such that
          <m>a = qn+r</m> and <m>0 \le r \lt n</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                The integer <m>q</m> is the <term>quotient</term> of <m>a \div n</m>.
                When <m>a \ge 0</m>,
                it is the number of cookies per child in the story.
                For example, the quotient when <m>23 \div 4</m> is five.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                We write <m>a</m> <c>div</c> <m>n =q</m>.
                For example, <m>23</m> <c>div</c> <m>4=5</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The integer <m>r</m> is the <term>remainder</term> of <m>a \div n</m>.
                When <m>a \ge 0</m>, it is the number of cookies for me.
                For example, the remainder when <m>23 \div 4</m> is three.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                We write <m>a</m> <c>mod</c> <m>n=r</m>.
                For example, <m>23</m> <c>mod</c> <m>4=3</m>.
                In many computer programming languages,
                <c>mod</c> is denoted using the percent symbol (%).
                For example, we would write <m>23 \% 4 = 3</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                We say <m>a \div n</m> is <m>q</m>
                <term>with remainder</term> <m>r</m>.
                For example, <m>23 \div 4</m> is five with remainder three.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                In <term>long division</term> the quotient is typically written at the top of the bar and the remainder is the final number at the bottom,
                as in <xref ref="fig_longdivision_23div4"></xref>.
                <figure xml:id="fig_longdivision_23div4">
                  <caption>Long division calculation for <m>23 \div 4</m>.</caption>
                  \intlongdivision{23}{4}
                </figure>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Let's see these definitions in action.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_quo_rem_div_mod">
      <title>Quotient, Remainder, \fn{div}, and \fn{mod}</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          On this problem we do not use computational technology
          (except to check).
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Find the quotient and the remainder when <m>100 \div 9</m>.
                Use your answer to calculate <m>100</m> <c>div</c> <m>9</m> and <m>100</m> <c>mod</c> <m>9</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Starting with 100 cookies,
                    we recognize that <m>9 \times 11 = 99</m> and so we can hand each child 11 cookies,
                    leaving us with <m>100 - (11\times 9) = 100-99 = 1</m> cookie.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    If we were using computational technology,
                    we could calculate <m>100 \div 9 = 11.1111.</m>.. and again see that 11 is the largest number of cookies we can give each child,
                    as there are not enough cookies to give each child 12 cookies.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    If we did a long division instead,
                    we would get the same answer,
                    as shown in <xref ref="fig_longdivision_23div4"></xref>.
                  </p>
                  <figure xml:id="fig_longdivision_100div9">
                    <caption>Long division calculation for <m>100 \div 9</m>.</caption>
                    \intlongdivision{100}{9}
                  </figure>
                  <p>
                    Notice that in the long division we calculate the remainder in two steps.
                    First, we give each child 10 cookies for a total of
                    <m>10 \times 9 = 90</m> cookies (although 0 is not written),
                    so the remainder is <m>100-90 = 10</m>.
                    Next, we give each child 1 cookie for a total of <m>1 \times 9 = 9</m> cookies,
                    so the final remainder is <m>10-9=1</m>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Using any way of thinking of this division, we get
                    <me>
                      100 = 11(9) +1
                    </me>,
                    so the quotient is 11 and the remainder is 1.
                    Thus, <m>100</m> <c>div</c> <m>9=11</m> and <m>100</m> <c>mod</c> <m>9=1</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Find the quotient and the remainder when <m>35 \div 5</m>.
                Use your answer to calculate <m>35</m> <c>div</c> <m>5</m> and <m>35</m> <c>mod</c> <m>5</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Write <m>35 = 7(5)</m> so the quotient is seven.
                    To find the remainder, think of the equation as
                    <m>35 = 7(5)+0</m>, so the remainder is zero.
                    Thus, <m>35</m> <c>div</c> <m>5=7</m> and <m>35</m> <c>mod</c> <m>5=0</m>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use the <c>mod</c> notation (or %) to describe whether an integer is even or odd.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    An integer <m>n</m> is even if <m>n=2k</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.
                    When we divide,
                    we get <m>n \div 2 = k</m> and the remainder is zero.
                    Thus, <m>n</m> is even exactly when <m>n</m> <c>mod</c> <m>2=0</m> or,
                    equivalently, when <m>n\%2=0</m>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    An integer <m>n</m> is odd if <m>n=2k+1</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.
                    When we divide,
                    we get <m>n \div 2 = k</m>, and the remainder is one.
                    Thus, <m>n</m> is even exactly when <m>n</m> <c>mod</c> <m>2=1</m> or,
                    equivalently, when <m>n\%2=1</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      It is your turn to practice.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_practice_div_mod">
      <title>Practice with Div and Mod</title>
      <p>
        In this activity, do all calculations by hand.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find the quotient and the remainder when <m>73 \div 7</m>.
              State your answer using <c>div</c> and <c>mod</c>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find the quotient and the remainder when <m>66 \div 6</m>.
              State your answer using <c>div</c> and <c>mod</c>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find the quotient and the remainder when <m>3 \div 10</m>.
              State your answer using <c>div</c> and <c>mod</c>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_mod10">
            <p>
              Calculate <m>27</m> <c>mod</c> 10, 115 <c>mod</c> 10,
              and \text{ 123,456,789 } <c>mod</c> 10.
              Hint: Subtract multiples of 10.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              What do you notice in <xref ref="part_mod10"/>?
              State your answer as a conjecture.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              For a nonnegative integer <m>a</m>,
              what are the possible values of <m>a</m> <c>mod</c> <m>10</m>?
              State your answer as a conjecture.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              For a nonnegative integer <m>a</m> and an integer <m>n \ge 1</m>,
              what are the possible values of <m>a</m> <c>mod</c> <m>n</m>?
              State your answer as a conjecture.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_polys">
    <title>\subpolys</title>
    <p>
      The Division Algorithm <xref ref="thm_div_alg"/> gives us expressions such as <m>2k+1</m> for an odd integer or <m>3q+2</m> for an integer where that integer <m>\fn{mod}~ 3 = 2</m>.
      We might square an even integer to get an expression of the form <m>4n^2</m>.
      These expressions are polynomials.
      In this section, we take a look at polynomials,
      including how to simplify products and powers.
      We start with the definition.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_polynomials">
      <title>Polynomials</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                For an integer <m>n</m>,
                a <em>polynomial</em> in <m>n</m> is a sum of constant multiples of powers of <m>n</m>.
                For example, <m>2m^4+5m^2-m+7</m> is a polynomial in <m>m</m>.
                To see why, we can rewrite this polynomial to show the powers of <m>n</m>.
                <me>
                  2m^4+5m^2-m+7=2(m^4)+5(m^2)+(-1)(m^1)+7(m^0)
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                In a polynomial,
                the integer in front of a power of <m>n</m> is the <term>coefficient</term>
                of that power of <m>n</m>.
                For example, in the polynomial <m>2m^3+5m^2-m+7</m>,
                the coefficient of <m>m^4</m> is 2, the coefficient of <m>m^2</m> is 5, the coefficient of <m>m</m> is <m>-1</m>,
                and the coefficient of <m>m^3</m> is 0.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                In a polynomial, the coefficient of <m>m^0</m> is the
                <term>constant term</term>.
                For example, the constant term of <m>2m^3+5m^2-m+7</m> is 7.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                We add polynomials by <em>collecting like terms</em>.
                For example
                <me>
                  (k^3 + 2k -7) + (4k^3 + k^2 + 2) = (k^3+4k^3) + (k^2) + (2k) + (-7 +2) = 5k^3+k^2+2k-5
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                To multiply or <term>expand</term>
                a product of polynomials,
                we use the distributive rule.
                See, for example, <xref ref="exam_mult_polys"></xref>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      We use the distributive rule <xref ref="defn_integer_algebra_order_operations"/> to expand polynomials.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_mult_polys">
      <title>Multiplying polynomials</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Expand <m>n^2(2n+1)</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    By the distributive rule,
                    <me>
                      n^2(2n+1) = n^2(2n) + n^2(1) = 2n^3+n^2
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Expand <m>(n+2)(n+3)</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    By the distributive rule (repeatedly),
                  </p>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>(n+3)(n+2)</m></cell>
                      <cell>=</cell>
                      <cell><m>n(n+2) + 3(n+2)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell>=</cell>
                      <cell><m>\underbrace{(n)(n)}_{\text{ First } } +\underbrace{(n)(2)}_{\text{ Outside } } + \underbrace{(3)(n)}_{\text{ Inside } } + \underbrace{(3)(2)}_{\text{ Last } }</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell>=</cell>
                      <cell><m>n^2 + 2n + 3n + 6</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell>=</cell>
                      <cell><m>n^2+5n + 6</m></cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                  <p>
                    The words under each product indicate the original location of the two integers that are multiplied.
                    This method is <term>First, Outside, Inside, Last</term> or <term>FOIL</term>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      There is a nice set of visualizations<fn>
      This lesson is from the College Algebra Foundations course by Lumen Learning retrieved from \url{https://tinyurl.com/vizpolymult}.
      </fn> of multiplying polynomials in <m>x</m> as areas at \url{https://tinyurl.com/vizpolymult}. Try your hand at multiplying polynomials with discrete variables.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_mult_polys">
      <title>Multiplying polynomials</title>
      <p>
        Expand and simplify each expression.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>2n(3n^2+2n-1)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>(k-2)(k+1)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>(m+1)^2</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>(2q+1)^2</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>(n+3)(n-3)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>(n+b)(n-b)</m> for any integer <m>b</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_pff_cases">
    <title>\subpffcases</title>
    <p>
      We can use the Division Algorithm <xref ref="thm_div_alg"/> to prove that every integer is even or odd,
      but never both.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_every_integer_even_or_odd">
      <title>Every integer is even or odd</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the Division Algorithm <xref ref="thm_div_alg"/> to prove that every integer is even or odd.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <em>Proof</em> Let <m>a</m> be an integer.
          By the Division Algorithm <xref ref="thm_div_alg"/> with <m>n=2</m>,
          there exist unique integers <m>q</m> and <m>r</m> such that <m>a=qn+r</m> and <m>0 \le r \lt 2</m>.
          Note that <m>r=0</m> or <m>r=1</m>.
          Since <m>r</m> is unique, we are in exactly one of these two cases.
          Case 1: Assume <m>r=0</m>.
          Then <m>a = 2q+0 = 2q</m> is even,
          by the definition of even.
          Case 2: Assume <m>r=1</m>.
          Then <m>a=2q+1</m> is odd, by the definition of odd.
          In either case <m>a</m> is even or <m>a</m> is odd.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      As in <xref ref="exam_every_integer_even_or_odd"></xref>,
      the Division Algorithm <xref ref="thm_div_alg"/> can be used to break a proof into cases,
      similar to how we break counting arguments into cases in <xref ref="sec_counting_steps_cases"></xref>.
      Here is the proof format.
    </p>
    <proof>
    <p>
      Prove: <m>P</m>
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        (Explain why there are <m>n</m> cases.) We consider <m>n</m> cases.
      </p>
      <p>
        Case 1: Assume <ellipsis/> (Explain why <m>P</m> is true in this case.)
      </p>
      <p>
        Case 2: Assume <ellipsis/> (Explain why <m>P</m> is true in this case.)
      </p>
      <p>
        <ellipsis/>
      </p>
      <p>
        Case <m>n</m>: Assume <ellipsis/> (Explain why <m>P</m> is true in this case.)
      </p>
      <p>
        In (either case/all cases) we have <m>P</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    </proof>
    <p>
      In a proof by cases,
      it is important that the cases cover all of the possibilities.
      Sometimes we need to explain that up front.
      The phrase
      <q>We consider <m>n</m> cases</q>
      that alerts the reader that we are using a proof by cases.
      The assumption for each case
      <q>Assume that <ellipsis/></q>. is stated as a complete sentence
      (with a period at the end)
      before any additional argument is presented.
      After we finish the cases, we summarize using the phrase
      <q>in either case</q>. If there are more than two cases, we use
      <q>in all cases</q>.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_proof_cases_nsqplusn_even">
      <title>Proof by Cases: <m>n^2 + n</m> is even</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_proof_cases_read">
            <p>
              Copy the following example of a proof by cases.
              Prove that <m>n^2+n</m> is even for any integer <m>n</m>.
              <proof>
                <p>
                  Let <m>n</m> be an integer.
                  <xref ref="exam_every_integer_even_or_odd">By</xref>,
                  <m>n</m> is even or <m>n</m> is odd.
                  We consider two cases.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Case 1: Assume <m>n</m> is even.
                  By the definition of even, <m>n = 2k</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.
                  Thus
                  <me>
                    n^2+n=(2k)^2+(2k) = 4k^2+2k = 2(2k^2+k)
                  </me>,
                  so <m>n^2+n</m> is even.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Case 2: Assume <m>n</m> is odd.
                  By the definition of odd, <m>n=2k+1</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.
                  Thus
                  <me>
                    n^2+n= (2k+1)^2 +(2k+1) = 4k^2 + 4k + 1 + 2k + 1 = 4k^2 + 6k + 2 = 2(2k^2 + 3k + 1)
                  </me>,
                  so <m>n^2+n</m> is even.
                </p>
                <p>
                  In either case, <m>n^2+n</m> is even.
                </p>
              </proof>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Edit the proof in <xref ref="part_proof_cases_read"/> to prove that <m>n^2 - n</m> is even for any integer <m>n</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      We give another example of proof by cases.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_product_3consec_mult3">
      <title>Using proof by cases to prove multiple of three</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use a proof by cases to prove
          <me>
            3 \mid n(n+1)(n+2)
          </me>
          for any integer <m>n</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let <m>n</m> be an integer.
          By the Division Algorithm <xref ref="thm_div_alg"/>, we can write
          <me>
            n=3q+r
          </me>
          for some integers <m>q</m> and <m>r</m> with <m>0 \le r \lt  3</m>.
          The only possible values of <m>r</m> are <m>r=0</m>,
          <m>r=1</m>, and <m>r=2</m>.
          We consider three cases.
        </p>
        <p>
          Case 1: Assume <m>r=0</m>.
          In this case, <m>n=3q</m> and so
          <me>
            n(n+1)(n+2)= (3q)(3q+1)(3q+2) = 3[q(3q+1)(3q+2)] = 3k
          </me>
          where <m>k = q(3q+1)(3q+2)</m>.
          Thus, <m>3\mid n(n+1)(n+2)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Case 2: Assume <m>r=1</m>.
          In this case, <m>n=3q+1</m> and so
          <me>
            n(n+1)(n+2)= (3q+1)(3q+2)(3q+3) = (3q+1)(3q+2)3(q+1) =3[(3q+1)(3q+2)(q+1)] = 3k
          </me>
          where <m>k = (3q+1)(3q+2)(q+1)</m>.
          Thus, <m>3\mid n(n+1)(n+2)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Case 3: Assume <m>r=2</m>.
          In this case, <m>n=3q+2</m> and so
          <me>
            n(n+1)(n+2)= (3q+2)(3q+3)(3q+4) = (3q+2)3(q+1)(3q+4) = 3[(3q+2)(q+1)(3q+4)] = 3k
          </me>
          where <m>k = (3q+2)(q+1)(3q+4)</m>.
          Thus, <m>3\mid n(n+1)(n+2)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          In all cases, <m>3\mid n(n+1)(n+2)</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_division_algorithm">for</xref> \subdivalg</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_find_quotient_remainder">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do not use technology or other resources.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Find the quotient and the remainder when <m>100 \div 3</m>.
                  State your answer using <c>div</c> and <c>mod</c>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Calculate 20 <c>div</c> 7 and 20 <c>mod</c> 7.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Explain your answers to (b) using the context of children and cookies as in <xref ref="exam_cookies_children"></xref>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_mod2_even_odd">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Evaluate each of the following integers: 3 <c>mod</c> 2, 4 <c>mod</c> 2, 5 <c>mod</c> 2, 6 <c>mod</c> 2, 28 <c>mod</c> 2, 125 <c>mod</c> 2.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Which integers have <m>n</m> <c>mod</c> <m>2 = 0</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Which integers have <m>n</m> <c>mod</c> <m>2 = 1</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_examples_mod">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            On this problem, no justification is required.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Give an example of an integer <m>n</m> with
                  <m>100 \le n \le 200</m> and <m>n</m> <c>mod</c> 2 = 1.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Give an example of an integer <m>n</m> with
                  <m>100 \le n \le 200</m> and <m>n</m> <c>mod</c> 3 = 1.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Give an example of an integer <m>n</m> with
                  <m>100 \le n \le 200</m> and <m>n</m> <c>mod</c> 7 = 1.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Give an example of an integer <m>n</m> with
                  <m>100 \le n \le 200</m> and <m>n</m> <c>mod</c> 10 = 1.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_mod10_practice">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Evaluate each of the following: 21 <c>mod</c> 10, 37 <c>mod</c> 10, 43 <c>mod</c> 10, 59 <c>mod</c> 10,
                  and 60 <c>mod</c> 10.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Give an example of positive integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> where
                  <m>2a \fn{ mod } 10 = 2b \fn{ mod } 10</m> but <m>a \fn{ mod } 10 \neq b \fn{ mod } 10</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Give an example of integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> where
                  <m>n \fn{ mod } 10 \neq 0</m> and <m>m \fn{ mod } 10 \neq 0</m>,
                  but <m>nm \fn{ mod } 10 = 0</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_modn">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider an integer <m>n \ge 1</m>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What are the values of <m>0</m> <c>div</c> <m>n</m> and <m>0</m> <c>mod</c> <m>n</m>?
                  Explain.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What are the values of <m>n</m> <c>div</c> <m>n</m> and <m>n</m> <c>mod</c> <m>n</m>?
                  Explain.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>a</m> is an integer with <m>0 \le a \lt n</m>,
                  what can you say about <m>a</m> <c>div</c> <m>n</m> and <m>a</m> <c>mod</c> <m>n</m>?
                  Explain.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_cases_mod3_mod10">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li xml:id="part_div_alg_mod3">
                <p>
                  Use the Division Algorithm <xref ref="thm_div_alg"/> to explain how any integer can be written in the form <m>3q</m>,
                  <m>3q+1</m>, or <m>3q+2</m>.
                  Hint: We used this fact in <xref ref="exam_product_3consec_mult3"></xref>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_div_alg_mod10">
                <p>
                  Use the Division Algorithm <xref ref="thm_div_alg"/> to explain how any integer <m>n</m> can be written in the form <m>n=10q+s</m> where <m>s</m> is a digit,
                  namely the last digit of <m>n</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_div_alg">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the Division Algorithm says?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What restrictions are on the remainder <m>r</m> when we calculate <m>n \div a</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to calculate <c>div</c> and <c>mod</c> using long division?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_calculate_div_mod_division">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Calculate 247 <c>div</c> 18 and 247 <c>mod</c> 18.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Note that <m>247 \div 18= 13.7222\ldots</m>.
                  Explain how we could calculate 247 <c>div</c> 18 using this equation.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  In general, if we know the decimal number <m>n \div a</m>,
                  how can we find <m>a</m> <c>div</c> <m>n</m>?
                  You may describe your answer in words.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Again, note that <m>247 \div 18= 13.7222\ldots</m>.
                  Explain how we could calculate 247 <c>mod</c> 18 using this equation.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  In general, if we know the decimal number
                  <m>n \div a</m> and we know <m>a</m> <c>div</c> <m>n</m>,
                  how can we find <m>a</m> <c>mod</c> <m>n</m>.
                  You may describe your answer in words.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_isbn">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The International Standard Book Number (ISBN) is a 13-digit integer used to identify a book.
            The last digit is calculated from the first 12 digits and is used to check whether a 13-digit number is a legitimate ISBN. This <em>check digit</em>
            is useful to avoid copying errors.
            Here is how.
            For
            <me>
              \text{ ISBN }  = abcdefghijkmx
            </me>
            the 13th check digit <m>x</m> is chosen so that
            <me>
              (a + 3b + c + 3d + e + 3f + g + 3h + i + 3j + k + 3m + x) \fn{ mod } 10 = 0
            </me>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Confirm that 9780691151649 is a valid ISBN. Note that <m>a=9</m>,
                  <m>b=7</m>, <ellipsis/>, <m>x=9</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Calculate the check digit for the ISBN beginning 123450123450.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_polys">for</xref> \subpolys</title>
      <exercise>
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What is the coefficient of <m>n^2</m> in the polynomial <m>5n^3-n^2+3n+8</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What is the constant term of the polynomial <m>5n^3-n^2+3n+8</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What is the coefficient of <m>k</m> in the polynomial <m>5k^2+k</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What is the constant term of the polynomial <m>5k^2+k</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_expanding_polys">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Expand and simplify.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>n(2n^2+1)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(k+1)(k+3)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(m-1)(m+1)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_square_polys">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Expand and simplify.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(n+1)^2</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(2k+1)^2</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(m+2)^2-(m-1)^2</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_polys">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What a polynomial is?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to multiply polynomials or square a polynomial?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the abbreviation FOIL stands for?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_last_digit_square">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="exer_cases_mod3_mod10">By</xref><xref ref="part_div_alg_mod10"/>,
            we can write a positive integer <m>a</m> as <m>a=10q+s</m> for some integers <m>q</m> and <m>s</m> where <m>s</m> is the last digit of <m>a</m>.
            Note that <m>s=0,1,2,\ldots,9</m>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Expand and simplify <m>a^2</m> in terms of <m>q</m> and <m>s</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_last_digit_sq">
                <p>
                  Show that <m>a^2-s^2</m> is a multiple of 10.
                  It follows that <m>a^2</m> <c>mod</c> 10 <m>=s^2</m> <c>mod</c> 10 and therefore the last digit of <m>a^2</m> is equal to the last digit of <m>s^2</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_digit_sq">
                <p>
                  What are the possible last digits of <m>s^2</m>?
                  Hint: Recall that <m>s</m> is a digit,
                  so you can check each value of <m>s=0,1,2,\ldots,9</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What are the possible last digits of any integer <m>a^2</m>?
                  Hint: Use the results of <xref ref="part_last_digit_sq"/> and <xref ref="part_digit_sq"/>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_pff_cases">for</xref> \subpffcases</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_quadratic_even">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For any integer <m>n</m>,
            copy and edit the proof in <xref ref="act_proof_cases_nsqplusn_even"></xref> to prove that
            <me>
              n^2+3n+1
            </me>
            is odd for any integer <m>n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_cases_3divides">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Copy and edit the proof in <xref ref="exam_product_3consec_mult3"></xref> to prove
            <me>
              3 \mid n(n+1)(n-1)
            </me>
            for any integer <m>n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_pff_cases">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to write a proof by cases?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What needs to be true about the list of cases in a proof-by-cases?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How we can use the Division Algorithm to create cases for a proof by cases?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_cases_not_mult_three">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/> Use proof by cases <xref ref="pff_cases"/> to prove
            <me>
              3 \nmid 2n^2 +n+1
            </me>
            for any integer <m>n</m>.
            Hint: <xref ref="exer_cases_mod3_mod10">Use</xref>
            <xref ref="part_div_alg_mod3"/> to create three cases.
            Notice that we are proving something is not a multiple of three.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_cases_square_mod4">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use cases <xref ref="pff_cases"/> to prove that <m>n^2</m> <c>mod</c> <m>4 = 0</m> or <m>n^2</m> <c>mod</c> <m>4 = 1</m> for any integer <m>n</m>.
            Hint: Use cases based on whether <m>n</m> is even or <m>n</m> is odd.
            Note that in one case we get <m>n^2</m> <c>mod</c> <m>4 = 0</m> and in the other case we get <m>n^2</m> <c>mod</c> <m>4 = 1</m>.
            Officially, we are using a modified version of proof by cases that we revisit in <xref ref="sec_logic_connectives"></xref>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_cases_square_mod3">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use cases <xref ref="pff_cases"/> to prove that <m>n^2</m> <c>mod</c> <m>3 = 0</m> or <m>n^2</m> <c>mod</c> <m>3 = 1</m> for any integer <m>n</m>.
            Hint: <xref ref="exer_cases_mod3_mod10">Use</xref>
            <xref ref="part_div_alg_mod3"/> and consider three cases.
            Note that in one case we get <m>n^2</m> <c>mod</c> <m>3 = 0</m> and in the other two cases we get <m>n^2</m> <c>mod</c> <m>3 = 1</m>.
            Officially, we are using a modified version of proof by cases that we revisit in <xref ref="sec_logic_connectives"></xref>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Select Answers and Hints</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_find_quotient_remainder"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>100 \fn{ div } 3 = 33</m> and <m>100 \fn{ mod }3 = 1</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            2, 6
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Imagine 7 children.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_examples_mod"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Check that your answer is between 100 and 200 and odd.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Check that your answer is one more than a multiple of three.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: for example, <m>7 \times 20 = 140</m>,
            and so 141 is a possible example.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Any example is of the form <m>1d1</m> where <m>d</m> is a digit.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_mod10_practice"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answers in some order are <m>0,1,3,7,9</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: One way to build an example is to pick <m>a</m> and use <m>b=a+5</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Neither <m>n</m> nor <m>m</m> should be a multiple of 10.
            Try picking an even integer for <m>n</m> and an odd multiple of five for <m>m</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_modn"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answers in some order are 0 and <m>n</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answers in some order are 0 and 1.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answers in some order are 0 and <m>a</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_cases_mod3_mod10"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: By the Division Algorithm,
            <m>a=3q+r</m> where <m>0 \le r \lt 3</m>.
            What are the possible values of the integer <m>r</m>?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Explain why <m>0 \le s \lt 10</m> and so <m>s</m> is the last digit of <m>n</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_isbn"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Calculate <m>(9 + 3 \cdot 7 +8 + 3 \cdot 0 + \ldots ) \fn{ mod } 10</m>.
            You should get zero.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>x=4</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_expanding_polys"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>2n^3+n</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The coefficient of <m>k</m> in the answer is 4.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The constant term of the answer is <m>-1</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_square_polys"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The coefficient of <m>n</m> in the answer is 2.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: In the answer <m>k^2</m> and <m>k</m> have the same coefficient.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>6m+3</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_cases_mod3_mod10"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>a^2=\underline{\hspace{0.5in}}q^2 + \underline{\hspace{0.5in}}qs + \underline{\hspace{0.5in}}s^2</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
