    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_quadratic_even"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: In the case where <m>n=2k+1</m>,
        expand and simplify <m>(2k+1)^2+3(2k+1)+1=4k^2+10k+5 = 2(\underline{\hspace{0.5in}})+1</m>.
        Then, fill in the parentheses.
        If you need to,
        set it equal to <m>2m+1</m> and solve for <m>m</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_cases_3divides"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: As in the proof in <xref ref="exam_product_3consec_mult3"></xref>,
        keep the product in factored form and find a way to factor out a three from one of the factors.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
